import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import seaborn as sns

# 1. Dataset shape
data_shape = df.shape

# 2. Column names and data types
column_info = df.dtypes

# 3. Missing values per column
missing_values = df.isnull().sum()
missing_percentage = (missing_values / len(df)) * 100

# 4. Visualize missing values with a bar chart
plt.figure(figsize=(12, 6))
sns.barplot(x=missing_values.index, y=missing_values.values)
plt.xticks(rotation=45, ha='right')
plt.ylabel("Number of Missing Values")
plt.title("Missing Values per Column")
plt.tight_layout()
plt.show()

# 5. Drop duplicates
duplicate_count = df.duplicated().sum()
df_cleaned = df.drop_duplicates()

# Summarize cleaned shape and duplicate count
cleaned_shape = df_cleaned.shape

import pandas as pd

# 1. Load the data
file_path = r"C:\Users\tansi\Downloads\Dataset-Pyhton-001\Dataset\car_prices.csv"

                     .groupby('make', as_index=False)['sellingprice']

import pandas as pd

file_path = r"C:\Users\tansi\Downloads\Dataset-Pyhton-001\Dataset\car_prices.csv"

# Load in chunks to avoid memory issues
chunksize = 100_000
state_totals = {}

for chunk in pd.read_csv(file_path, usecols=['year', 'state', 'sellingprice'], chunksize=chunksize):
    filtered = chunk[chunk['year'] > 2013]
    group = filtered.groupby('state')['sellingprice'].agg(['sum', 'count'])

    for state, row in group.iterrows():
        if state in state_totals:
            state_totals[state]['sum'] += row['sum']
            state_totals[state]['count'] += row['count']
        else:
            state_totals[state] = {'sum': row['sum'], 'count': row['count']}

# Calculate average
avg_price_by_state = pd.DataFrame([
    {'state': state, 'avg_sellingprice': val['sum'] / val['count']}
    for state, val in state_totals.items()
])

# Sort and get top state
avg_price_by_state = avg_price_by_state.sort_values('avg_sellingprice', ascending=False)
print(avg_price_by_state.head())

import pandas as pd
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import seaborn as sns

# Load dataset
file_path = r"C:\Users\tansi\Downloads\Dataset-Pyhton-001\Dataset\car_prices.csv"
df = pd.read_csv(file_path)

# Step 1: Create condition bins of size 5
bins = range(0, 105, 5)  # From 0 to 100 in steps of 5
labels = [f"{i}-{i+4}" for i in bins[:-1]]
df['condition_bin'] = pd.cut(df['condition'], bins=bins, labels=labels, include_lowest=True)

# Step 2: Group by condition_bin and calculate average selling price
avg_price_by_condition = df.groupby('condition_bin')['sellingprice'].mean().reset_index()

# Step 3: Plot
plt.figure(figsize=(14, 6))
sns.barplot(data=avg_price_by_condition, x='condition_bin', y='sellingprice', palette='viridis')

plt.title('Average Selling Price by Condition Score Range (Bin Size = 5)')
plt.xlabel('Condition Score Range')
plt.ylabel('Average Selling Price ($)')
plt.xticks(rotation=45)
plt.tight_layout()
plt.show()
